  "text": "Another important finding of this study was that children did not have BMI-for-age measured, and were not likely to receive education about weight, diet, or exercise. Although BMI-for-age was never noted, growth charts were often used and provided a method to monitor growth for children up to 10 years of age. Unfortunately, after age 10, there was a significant decline in the use of growth charts. It is known that puberty is a critical time for the development of overweight, [CITATION_1] and unfortunately, these adolescents were not being monitored with BMI-for-age or growth charts.",
